Given, $$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0 &amp; { - 2}  \cr 
   2 &amp; { - 3} &amp; 4  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>We have, $$2X + 3A = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow X = {{ - 3} \over 2}A$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow X =  - {3 \over 2}\left[ {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 0 &amp; { - 2}  \cr 
   2 &amp; { - 3} &amp; 4  \cr 

 } } \right]$$,<br><br>$$X = \left[ {\matrix{
   { - {3 \over 2}} &amp; 0 &amp; 3  \cr 
   { - 3} &amp; {{9 \over 2}} &amp; { - 6}  \cr 

 } } \right]$$

Let $$\Delta  = \left| {\matrix{
   a &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; c  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = a(bc - 1) - 1(c - 1) + 1(1 - b)$$<br><br>$$ = abc - a - b - c + 2$$<br><br>$$ \because $$ $$\Delta  &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \therefore $$ $$abc - a - b - c + 2 &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow abc + 2 &gt; a + b + c$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow abc + 2 &gt; 3{(abc)^{1/3}}$$<br><br>[$$\because$$ a $$\ne$$ b $$\ne$$ c $$\Rightarrow$$ AM of a, b, c &gt; GM of $$a,b,c \Rightarrow {{a + b + c} \over 3} &gt; {(abc)^{1/3}}$$ $$ \Rightarrow a + b + c &gt; 3{(abc)^{1/3}}$$]<br><br>Now, let $$x = {(abc)^{1/3}}$$, then we have<br><br>$${x^3} + 2 &gt; 3x$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {x^3} - 3x + 2 &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {(x - 1)^2}(x + 2) &gt; 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow x + 2 &gt; 0$$ [$$\because$$ $${(x - 1)^2} &gt; 0$$]<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow x &gt;  - 2$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow {(abc)^{1/3}} &gt;  - 2$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow abc &gt;  - 8$$

Given, x + a + b + c = 0<br><br>$$\left| {\matrix{
   {x + a} &amp; b &amp; c  \cr 
   a &amp; {x + b} &amp; c  \cr 
   a &amp; b &amp; {x + c}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   {x + a + b + c} &amp; b &amp; c  \cr 
   {x + a + b + c} &amp; {x + b} &amp; c  \cr 
   {x + a + b + c} &amp; b &amp; {x + c}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>[by $${C_1} \to {C_1} + {C_2} + {C_3}$$]<br><br>$$ = (x + a + b + c)\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; b &amp; c  \cr 
   1 &amp; {x + b} &amp; c  \cr 
   1 &amp; b &amp; {x + c}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>[x + a + b + c common from C<sub>1</sub>] = 0<br><br>[$$\because$$ x + a + b + c = 0]

We have, $$\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; {1 + xyz} &amp; 1  \cr 
   1 &amp; 1 &amp; {1 + xyz}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>C<sub>1</sub> $$\to$$ C<sub>1</sub> $$-$$ C<sub>2</sub><br><br>$$ = \left| {\matrix{
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1  \cr 
   { - xyz} &amp; {1 + xyz} &amp; 1  \cr 
   0 &amp; 1 &amp; {1 + xyz}  \cr 

 } } \right|$$<br><br>$$ = xyz[(1 + xyz) - 1]$$ [expanding along C<sub>1</sub>]<br><br>$$ = {x^2}{y^2}{z^2}$$

Let $$A = \left[ {\matrix{
   2 &amp; 4  \cr 
   { - 8} &amp; x  \cr 

 } } \right]$$<br><br>Matrix does not have an inverse, if<br><br>$$\left| A \right| = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow 2x + 32 = 0$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow 2x =  - 32$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow x =  - {{32} \over 2}$$<br><br>$$ \Rightarrow x =  - 16$$

Let $$I = \int\limits_0^{\sqrt 2 } {[{x^2}]\,dx} $$<br><br>$$ = \int\limits_0^1 {[{x^2}]dx + \int\limits_1^{\sqrt 2 } {[{x^2}]\,dx} } $$<br><br>$$ = \int\limits_0^1 {0\,dx + \int\limits_1^{\sqrt 2 } {1\,dx} } $$<br><br>[$$\because$$ $$[x] = \left\{ {\matrix{
   {0,} &amp; {0 \le x &lt; 1}  \cr 
   {1,} &amp; {1 \le x &lt; \sqrt 2 }  \cr 

 } } \right.$$]<br><br>$$ = 0 + [x]_1^{\sqrt 2 } = \sqrt 2  - 1$$
